{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696386/1930091201/0060.xml":{"full_text":"30\nI\nIrregularity in Stock Price Trend to Continue Through Tomorrow\u2019s Session\nsms IRE MSMATING\nHIDHE\nAny Reaction at This Time Will Not Go Far,\nAvers Spectator\u2014Buy on Selloff He\nAdvises Trading Element\ni 'I,\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe market goes marching raggedly on, wavering here and\nperking up tb\u00bbe. I believe the Irregularity will prevail through\nout most of the session today and tomorrow.\nStocks seem to be resting and consolidating their recent ad\nvance. Yesterday weakness In wheat was a disturbing factor\nwhile there'Was ho counteracting good news from the business\nworld. This brought some .selling but the market held pretty\nFell. J,\nA reaction at this time isri\u2019t likely to go very far, and my\nadvice stiU is to pick up the leaders on any sell-off.\nBaldwin\nI hear that the best buying in\nBaldwin took place below 30 and\nthat the subsequent bulge to 35\nrecently was purely speculative in\ncharacter.\nBig interests are said to have\ntaken a large long position in\nBaldwin. This was somewhat due\nto the company\u2019s better earnings\nthis year and its ability to get a\nlarger share of the railroads loco\nmotive business, I understand, but\nmore to-the report that Baldwin\nis planning a large expansion\nprogram. This will be concen\ntrated in its machinery subsid\niaries it is said to add to the\ncompany\u2019s diversification of pro\nducts and work for greater sta\nbility of earnings. Those who are\nIn the know in Baldwin aren\u2019t\nbuying it at current levels, I am\ntold.\nIncrease of $33,000,000 in brok\ners\u2019 loans is further evidence of\nincreasing public participation in\nthe market. A number of broker\nage houses are reporting more in\nquiries from the man in the\nstreet, and some who have been\nout of the market since the Octo\nber-November \u2018conflagration\u2019 are\ncoming back for more.\nGillette\nAction oft Gillette the last few\ndays has trome out my predic\ntion a few days ago that the\nstock was around bottom and\nthat it was in a buying range.\nIt is up about 6 points since.\nI am told Gillette will shortly\nbring out a $20,000,000 bond is\nsue. The offering will be of a\nconvertible nature, It is said, and\nthe conversion price for the\nstock will be above current levels\nThe loan will be for the comple\ntion of the merger with Auto\nStrop, I understand.\nThere has been further short\ncovering in Gillette, I hear, one\nline of 30,000 shares that was\nput out last year between 123\nand 135 being taken in. Those\nwho bought the stock at my rec\n\u25a0EonE\nQUITS 0.5.\nBecause of its inability to\ncover operation costs, the Mich\nelin Tire Company, one of the\noldest tire companies operating\nin the United States, has com\npletely .diseontinued its produc\ntion in this country. Operations\nwill be continued in its home\nplant in France.\nJ. H. Michelin, vice president\nof the company, in explaining\nthe closing of the company\u2019s miy\nAmerican plant at Milltown, N.\nJ., stated that the reason fcr\nsuch action was that conditions\nin the tire business here mtyie it\nimposslbe to continue operations\nwith any chance of covering ex\npenses, it nos at a profit.\nThe company\u2019s Milltown plant,\nafter orerating since 1907, was\nshut down on May 1. this year.\nPrior to the closing of the plant\nabout 2,000 employes were laid\noff. A trust fund of approxi\nmately $700,000, set up some time\nago for employes\u2019 bonuses for\nthree years after they left the\ncompany, was recently announced\nas available to those who wished\ntheir share before the expiration\nof the time period. The com\npany has other factories in\nFrance and Italy. x\nThe Finest\nPersonal\nTransportation\nA.'\nLate model used cars\nof moderate price, con-\ntaining an unlimited\namount of unused\nmileage, are advertised\nfi nale daily in-\nClassified Ads\nWISHIiBTOi TTWBOISCIAL NEWS\nommendation should hold it for\nhigher prices.\nInsiders tell me that Kayser\nCo.\u2019s sales for August showed\na remarkable come-back over July\nthough they were lower than\nAugust last year. The company\nis believed to hate turned the\ncomer and the dividend require\nments are expected to be covered\nfor tjie September quarter: \u201day\nser is to a comfortable financial\nposition, the ratio of current as\nsets to current liabilities being\nbetter than 17 to 1.\nGeneral Motors\nGeneral Motors sloppy market\naction for the past few days is\nexplained to the report that earn\ning for the third Quarter may not\ncover the 75 cents dividend re\nquirement on the common. This\nwill probably cause some down\nward revision to the profits for the\nyear, estimated In some quarters\nat abput $4 a\u2019 share. At that\nMotors should cover its $3 divi\ndend with something to spare,\nand the effect on the stock mar\nket-wise probably won\u2019t be much.\nThere seems no reason, how\never, for any bull move in any\nof the motor stocks for a while.\nFew of the leaders expect any\nreal automobile buying to develop\nuntil next spring, and that\u2019s a\nbit too far off to start discount\ning now. There is the question,\ntoo, of whether all the bad news\nis out on the motors, for current\nselling prices of Hudson, Nash,\nStudebaker, and others raise\ndoubt as to the safety of their\ndividends.\nThe oils brightened up a bit\nand one floor trader said they\nlooked good for a move. There has\nbeen bullish news on the petro\nleum situation in the last few\ndays. Gasoline stocks are now\ndown more, refinery operations\nhave been reduced and the Julian\nwrit, threatening crude oil pro\nration, has been vacated in Okla\nhoma. Stick to the leaders, like\nJersey or Standard of California,\nif you-are going to play the oils.\nSTB\nFORTRADEGAIN\nThe business outlook of the\nRadio Corporation of America for\nthe last half of the year is con\nsiderably improved, according to\nDavid Samoff, president. He said\nthe public reception of the com\npany\u2019s new models was very grati\nfying and he looke for an in\ncreasing demand from now on.\n\u201cThe first six months activi\nties of the Radio Corporation\nare behind and the trying con\nditions which the company jwas\nsubject to in that period are\nonly too well known to com\nment on,\u201d he stated. \u201cFrom\nall current indications, however,'\nit does appear that our busi\nness is on the up trend and we\nare more than hopeful that\nthis condition will continue.\u201d\nMr. Samoff, who has been\nabroad for the past two months,\nsaid on his return:\n\u201cNo matter how bad off we\nmay think we are here to Ainer\niea, Europe\u2019s economic and fi\nnancial condition is much worse,\nand their improvement appears\nto depend upon oar own recov\nery\u201d\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock EarJiange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nM EMBER S\n1 J\nNew York Stock Exchange r\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nTo Leave\n\u2014Tlm\u00ab\u00bb Staff Photo\nJOHN B. LARNER\nPRESIDENT OF the Wash\nington Loan and Trust Com\npany, who will soon leave the\ncity for Mifflintown. Pa., where\nhe will resume his vacation.\nMr. Lamer maintains a sum\nmer residence there.\nBONUS SYSTEM\nRIPPED\nYOUNGSTOWN, Ohio. Sept. 12\n(LNJS.).\u2014Once again the bonus\nsystem of Bethlehem Steel Cor\nporation took the limelight in\nCommon Pleas Court here as op\nposing forces today continued\ntheir battle over the legality of\nthe merger of Bethlehem with\nYoungstown Sheet and Tube\nCompany.\nOpponents of the steel consoli\ndation renewed their attack in\nthe bonus matter through the\ncross-examination of W. B. Camp\nbell, partner in Price, Waterhouse\nand Company, the auditing con\ncern whose figures were the basis\nfor the merger terms.\nUnder questioning of Clan\nCrawford, anti-merger attorney.\nCampbell declared yesterday that\nhe did not consider the $3,400,000\npaid to Bethlehem executives un\nder the bonus system to 1929 as\nunusual but that he regarded it\n\u201cas part of Bethlehem\u2019s scheme\nof organization.\u201d\nApplication of Bethlehem\u2019s bo\nnus system unchanged to Sheet\nand Tube\u2019s 1929 earnings would\nhave reduced the earnings of\nBethlehem stock after merging\nwith the Youngstown concern by\nonly 30 cents a share, instead of\n$2 as claimed by the anti-merger\nists, Campbell declared.\nThe plaintiffs contend that the\n\u2022'unheard of\u201d bonuses paid by\nBethlehem support their theory\nthat the merger is unfair to Sheet\nand Tube stockholders.\nCampbell also testified that\nBethlehem\u2019s administrative and\nselling cost, including the bonus,\naveraged less than Sheet and\nTube\u2019s over a period of the last\nsix years.\nBritish Foreign\nTrade Off in August\nLONDON, Sept. 12.\u2014August\npreliminary British Foreign trade\nfigures show imports totaling\n\u00a370,923,000 against \u00a335,230,000 in\nJuly, and \u00a3100,993,000 in August\n1929. Exports were \u00a342,777.000,\nagainst \u00a350,740,000 in July, and\n\u00a363,045,000 in August last year.\nRe-exports in August were \u00a36,342,-\n000, against \u00a36,663,000 to July,\nand \u00a39,020,000 in August, 1929.\nWalker Telhof\nTraiuamerica Deal\nElisha Walker, chairman of the\nTransamerica Corporation, which\ncontrols Banca d\u2019America E\nd\u2019ltalia, states arrangements have\nbeen made whereby, subject to the\nusual legal formalties, Banca\nd\u2019America E d\u2019ltalia is taking over\nthe business of Fanca Italo Bri\ntannica ae of October 1, 1930. It\nis understood that the acquisition\nhas been effected in part for cash\nand in part for shares of Banca\nd\u2019America E d\u2019ltalia.\nAnderson Attacks\nFederal Reserve on\nCheap Money Policy\nFORT WAYNE, Ind., Sept. 12.\nThe Federal Reserve System was\ncriticized for its effort to create\ncheap money artificially by Ben\njamin M. Anderson, jr, economist,\nChase National Bank, New York.\nDr. Anderson sppke today before\nthe Indiana Bankers\u2019 Association.\n\u201cThe geld position of the Fed\neral Reserve System Is impreg\nnable,\u201d he said, fso far as the\nability of the system to maUtain\nthe gold standard and to meet\na tight money situation are\nconcerned. But the system\u2019s\ngold Is inadequate to permit an\nextension, dr even a continu\nance of the eheap money policy\nwhich manifests Itself to large\nholdings of Government secur\nites by the Federal Reserve\nbanks, unless the Federal Re\nserve System is willing to face\nthe necessity of a drastic re\nversal of policy and a sharp\nrise of interest rate whan the\ntrade revival begins.\u201d\nThe adequacy of the present\nvolume of free gold should be\njudged, Dr. Anderson declared,\nwith respect to the need of a\nperiod of normal activity rather\nthan with respect to the existing\ntrade depression and a season of\nthe year when money in circula\ntion is normally low, even in good\nyears.\nGold Depletion Causes\nSummarizing the effect of an\nattempt on the part of Federal\nReserve authorities to meet a\ntrade revival by increasing their\npurchases of Government securi\nties to such an\u00abextent as would\nhold money easy. Dr. Anderson\ndeclared that free gold would suf\nfer depletion from the following\ncauses:\n\u201c(1) a loss to money to cir\nculation of 300 million dollars\nas between the present period\nof depressed trade and the same\nperiod of a normal year, and of\nover 700 million dollars as be\ntween the low point of August,\n1930, and the peak of a normal\nDecember.\n\u201c(2) a loss of some gold to\nthe outside world, since the\noutside world would certainly be\nobliged to tighten interest rates\nin a trade revival, having much\nless 'free gold* than we have.\n\u201c(3) increased deposit reserve\nrequirements of a substantial\namount as member banks in\ncreased their commercial loans,\nwith corresponding increase of\n7><Wf* M\u00bbrk\nIMS-1330\n44 Year* of Constant\nProgress\nSTOCKETT AUC NO. 13\nThis is our Story and\nwe're going to Stick to it!\nStudying for Perfection.\nEvery one of ear sales\nrepresentatives is required to\ncomplete each month a pre\nscribed course of study in\nModern Office Practice, Ef\nficiency Devices, etc. As a\nresult they are equipped to\naid materially in solving\nyour office problems.\nThey know every item car\nried in our stock\u2014they are\nalso familiar with all of the\nnewest in Office Equipment,\neven though not m stock.\nThia remarkable fund of\ninformation is at your call.\nAsk to havq ono_>f our\nsales representatives sea you.\nSTpCKETT\nco\nWASHINCTOMDHO\nWASHINGTON TIMES'\n\u25a0uawsss erne* igj\u00bb M K a w\n\u2022ATM DEI4VEKBD MT caanruu to\nWASHINGTON AND ar PTsWTWTs\nMate per week,\n\u00bb\u2014<l\u2014 \u2014la M t e\n\u2022atm jh Marr.\ni grti\nDeify\ntheir deposits, and so needed\nlarger reserve balances with the\nFederal Reserve Baidu.\n*(4) increased deposit re\nserve requirements when the\nbanks of the country .experi\nenced a greatly increased de\nmand for money for stock mar\nket purposes, as the stock mar\nket, with the combination er\ncheap money and reviving\ntrade, began another great\nspeculative rise.\n\u201cThe practical conclusion\nfrom the foregoing consideration\nIs that the \u2019effective free geld\u2019\nwould not last long, and that\nbefore trade revival had gone\nvery far the Federal Reserve au\nthorities would be selling Gov\nernment securities, forcing the\nbanks to rediscount, and tight\nening the money market very\nsharply. The effect of this upon\nthe securities market would be\nmore important than upon\ntrade revival.\n\u201cA trade revival might go on,\nif soundly based, to the face of\na reaction in securities. Bank\ners would give the mercantile,\nmanufacturing and agricultural\nInterests of the country first\nclaim upon the loan funds, and\nthe securities market would\nhave to take what was left. But\nit would seem a wiser policy to\navoid the dangers which such a\nsituation would involve, to take\nup slack now, to make a mod\nerate reversal of policy now, and\nto be to a position to prevent\nearly radical changes to the\nmoney market when trade be\ngins to revive.\u201d\nTractor Exports\nSet New Record\nAmerican exports of tractors\nset a new all-time record in the\nfirst six months of the year, de\nspite the world wide economic\ndepression, the Commerce Depart\nment announced.\nmBMM e are pleased to\nannounce the open-\n1 mEmmml i ,l 8 \u00b0f \u00b0ffi ces n\nShoreham Build\ning at 810 Fifteenth\nStreet, North West\n.7'*\n_\n\n1\ne _\nt i'\nNew York\nTitle and Mortgage\nCompany\n1 f-i\nJEashevgtojv Branch\n\ni-.. ,\u2018z-'. 1\nCapital Fundi over $63,000,000\nB\nW. J. BOOHER, Manager B. B. BAILEY, Tide Officer\n\n\u25a0'\u25a0,\u25a0t 1\nTelephone MetrapeHtaa 390\u00ae\n\nI\nT _ 4\nFRIDAY, SEPTEMBER IE, 1080\nBROKERS STILE\nARE BULLISH\nSome Irregularity due to profit\ntaking was predicted foe the mar\nket to brokerage circles today.\nThe long side of the market was\nbelieved the best at the present\ntime, and while minor recessions\nwere forecast from time to time\nthe general trend was believed to\nbe upward.\nYesterday\u2019s market was quite\nsatisfactory. There was no signs\nof weakness In any place along\nthe line, while on the other hand\nnew points of strength made their\nappearance which bespoke genu\nine rather than an at\ntempt to create window dressing.\n\u2014BAAR, COHEN te CO.\nBelieve that the recovery in the\nstock market will proceed further.\n\u2014OTIS CO.\nSee opportunities for common\nstock investment. From a specu\nlative standpoint we think trad\ning for small profits on the long\nside are most likely to be suc\ncessful.\u2014E. F. HUTTON A CO.\nIn view of the situation we\nfeel strongly that the purchase of\nsound securities can be recom\nmended.\u2014M. J. MEEHAN CO.\nParmelee-Checker\nMerger Approved\nDirectors of the Parmelee\nTransportation Co., and the\nChecker Cab Manufacturing\nCorp, have unanimously ap\nproved the plan whereby the lat\nter corporation will acquire con\ntrol of the Parmelee company\nThe entire capital stock of the\nMotor Car Transportation Co.,\nlarge New York operating unit of\nParmelee, will' also be acquired\nby Checker.\nChecker now owns $1,442,000 of\nthe outstanding debentures of\nParmelee Transportation: all of\nthe $1,000,000 preferred stock\n23.000 shares of the common\nstock and warrants for the pur\nchase of 93,425 additional shares\nof common.\n...i\nSeashore\nLa 1\nq\n\u2014Time* Staff Phot#\nw. W. BPAID\nOF W. B. HIBBS AND CO.,\nmembers of the New York Stock\nExchange, who has gone to\nAtlantic City where he will\nspend a week's vacation.\nBig Copper Sales\nMade at 10% Cents\nTl 4 first week in September\nshowed little or no improvement in\nthe non-ferrous metal situation,\nthough demand for copper and\nlead has been the best for several\nweeks, and silver has again held\nabove 36 cents, reports Metal and\nMineral Markets. Tin continues\nto be available below 30 cents,\nwith demand only moderate and\nlargely speculative. Zinc buying\nhas dwindled to such an extent\nthat the 4J5 to 4.30 cent quota\ntion of the last three days is no\nmore than a nominal one.\nAlmost 11,000 tons of copper\nwere sold in the domestic market\nin the week ending yesterday,\nwhich represents the best week\u2019s\nbusiness since eary August. Sales,\nhowever, were not sufficient to\nabsorb all the offerings at 10%\ncents\nAIRCRAFT FIRM\nCHANGES\nA new and Interesting develop\nment in the aviation field wm\nbrought to light today with the\nannouncement of the reorganize\ntion of the Brunner-Winkle Air\ncraft Corporation, and the change\nin corporate name to the Bird Air\ncraft Corporation. This companv\nhas had a remarkable record dur\ning the past year and came into\ngreat prominence a few weeks ago\nwhen Colonel Lindbergh an\nnounced the purchase of a Bird\nairplane for his wife.\nThe. new directorate which was\nannounced at the same time, and\nwhich includes prominent repre\nsentatives of Detroit as well as\nNew York capital is as follows:\nCol. Henry Breckenridge, Major\nThos. G. Lanphler, Harry Messin\nger, William E. Winkle. Frank W.\nBrooks. jr M Detroit. 8. R. Living-\nstone. Detroit, Howard Bonty-ight,\nDetroit. Frederick C. Ford of De\ntroit and W. W. Mills.\nThe new board of directors an\nnounced the election of the fol\nlowing officers: Major Thos. G.\nLanphier. president, William E.\nWinkle, vice-president and general\nmanager, James Phelan, secretary\nand treasurer.\nThe executive committee con\nsists of Major Lanohier. W. E. I\nWinkle. F. W. Brooks, jr., and J\nHenry Breckenridge. 1\nMajor Thomas G. Lanphier has 1\nbeen Identified with airplanes for\nover IS years, having served as\nCommandant of the First Pursuit\nGroup at Selfridge Field. Major\nLanphier has also had considera\nble experience in the manufactur\ning end of the business and brings\nto the company a thorough under\nstanding as wen as one of the best\ninformed minds in the world on\nflying and aircraft development.\nJONIS UNGER BROS. CO.\nUnger Brothers Co., Inc., an- 4\nnounce that Otto J. Delia, for\nmerly with Clokey As Miller, has\nbecome associated with them as\nmanager of their trading depart\nment, specialising In bank and in\nsurancedstocks.","height":"30457","width":"24155"}}
